{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T06-41-43-154Z","slug":"developer-workstation-blast-radius","locale":"fr","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T06:42:09.370Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-09--developer-workstation-blast-radius/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-09--developer-workstation-blast-radius/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/developer-workstation-blast-radius/fr/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T06-41-43-154Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"2ea2b0fa3efd5f31a991b8add09b755aea04ca443ae149a0b177d9569acefeef","outputHash":"2a7dafa47dc85b4c871d7c994427cf7659bdecb757b32bd28967d8122a89e7f0","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that developer laptops should be hardened by limiting the “blast radius” of any code that runs with the user’s privileges, rather than relying on generic endpoint‑security checklists or extreme “no‑browser” advice. It proposes a four‑layer defense—Isolation, Secret handling, Detection, and Egress control—and shows how to implement each with practical, developer‑friendly tools. The core recommendations are: (1) run each project inside a tightly‑configured Dev Container that only mounts the workspace (avoiding home‑directory mounts and credential folders); (2) replace sprawling plaintext *.env* files with encrypted or managed secrets (e.g., using VarLock and a clear schema that marks sensitive values); and (3) augment the setup with canary tokens, monitoring, and outbound‑traffic controls. The tone is a pragmatic tutorial aimed at software engineers, team leads, and security‑conscious developers who need actionable steps without turning their workflow into “wet cement.” Recurring metaphors frame the problem as a “blast radius” and the solution as “containment” using containers, token “suitcases,” and “tripwires.”","totalInputTokens":39046,"t